        "text": "Our theoretical reporting will leave aside research that pursues a normative, rationality-seeking line, i.e. attempts to determine how certain results can be achieved as well as possible, as safely as possible or at minimum cost, and restrict ourselves to approaches that are explicitly or implicitly formulated with the aid of the concept of [[Causality]]. In terms of theoretical and methodological ambition, efforts are made to coordinate the distinction between cause and effect with other distinctions, for example between means and ends or between instruction and obedience or between group formation and motivation. In this meaning, it is **sociology with the intention of [[Explanation]]** and, where possible, prognosis; or also: with the intention of providing technical, advisory assistance in organizational planning. Business management research or developments in the field of business theory (theory of the firm) are also important in this respect; however, their evaluation in sociology is still hampered by subject and discipline boundaries or by the sheer volume of literature. Today, it is primarily initiated by analyzing the relationship between structures and decisions. We will return to this later."
